{"title_page": "Parada (Paredes de Coura)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name = Parada\n|image_shield =\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[Alto Minho]]\n|district           = [[Viana do Castelo District|Viana do Castelo]]\n|municipality       = [[Paredes de Coura]]\n|area_total = 5.90\n|population_total = 298\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates = {{coord|41.915|-8.526|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = [http://www.jf-parada-pcoura.com www.jf-parada-pcoura.com]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Parada''' is a civil parish in the municipality of [[Paredes de Coura]], Portugal. The population in 2011 was 298,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 5.90&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe parish is bounded with [[Padornelo (Portugal)|Padornelo]] to the north, [[Vasc\u00f5es]] and [[Bico e Cristelo]] to the south. The source of the [[Rio Coura]] is near the parish.\n\n==History==\n\nOn November 15, 1993, the Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Cultural Desportiva e Social de Parada was founded, its first president was Manuel Pereira Ara\u00fajo.  The association brings in the good ways in the strength of the youch in the sporting and cultural fields, it finds the enthusiasm that represents the name of the parish.  The vitality of its youths that won 42 cups and 3 medals.  One football (soccer) matches includes two first places with 13-15 in 1996 and in 1908, three second places, the other two were in 13-15 in 1995 and in 1997, it won three consecutive district titles along with inter-parish tournaments with 5-3 against Cunha in 1995 in penalty kicks, 1-0 against Resende in 1007 and 1-0 against Associa\u00e7\u00e3o de Paredes de Coura in 1998.  The soccer field was completed in 1998.\n\n==Economy==\nIts main economic activity is agriculture, civil construction and ultimately employment in the [[Castanheira (Paredes de Coura)|Castanheira]] industrial area, S\u00e3o Bento and in Cerveira.  Its main productions are corn, potatoes, wine and others.\n\n==Associations==\n*ACDSP \u2013 Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Cultural Desportiva e Social de Parada (Parada Sporting And Social Cultural Association)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paredes de Coura}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Paredes de Coura]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name = Parada\n|image_shield =\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[Alto Minho]]\n|district           = [[Viana do Castelo District|Viana do Castelo]]\n|municipality       = [[Paredes de Coura]]\n|area_total = 5.90\n|population_total = 298\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates = {{coord|41.915|-8.526|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = [http://www.jf-parada-pcoura.com www.jf-parada-pcoura.com]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Parada''' is a civil parish in the municipality of [[Paredes de Coura]], Portugal. The population in 2011 was 298,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 5.90&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page/portal/nuts_nomenclature/documents/PT-LAU.xls Eurostat]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe parish is bounded with [[Padornelo (Portugal)|Padornelo]] to the north, [[Vasc\u00f5es]] and [[Bico e Cristelo]] to the south. The source of the [[Rio Coura]] is near the parish.\n\n==History==\n\nOn November 15, 1993, the Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Cultural Desportiva e Social de Parada was founded, its first president was Manuel Pereira Ara\u00fajo.  The association brings in the good ways in the strength of the youch in the sporting and cultural fields, it finds the enthusiasm that represents the name of the parish.  The vitality of its youths that won 42 cups and 3 medals.  One football (soccer) matches includes two first places with 13-15 in 1996 and in 1908, three second places, the other two were in 13-15 in 1995 and in 1997, it won three consecutive district titles along with inter-parish tournaments with 5-3 against Cunha in 1995 in penalty kicks, 1-0 against Resende in 1007 and 1-0 against Associa\u00e7\u00e3o de Paredes de Coura in 1998.  The soccer field was completed in 1998.\n\n==Economy==\nIts main economic activity is agriculture, civil construction and ultimately employment in the [[Castanheira (Paredes de Coura)|Castanheira]] industrial area, S\u00e3o Bento and in Cerveira.  Its main productions are corn, potatoes, wine and others.\n\n==Associations==\n*ACDSP \u2013 Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Cultural Desportiva e Social de Parada (Parada Sporting And Social Cultural Association)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paredes de Coura}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Paredes de Coura]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parada_(Paredes_de_Coura)"}
{"title_page": "Panque", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Panque\n|image_shield = BCL-panque.gif\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 6.29\n|population_total = 680\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates   = {{coord|41.635|-8.595|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Panque''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[freguesia]]'' (\"civil parish\"), located in the municipality of [[Barcelos Municipality, Portugal|Barcelos]]. The population in 2011 was 680,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 6.29&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Barcelos}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Panque\n|image_shield = BCL-panque.gif\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 6.29\n|population_total = 680\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates   = {{coord|41.635|-8.595|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Panque''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[freguesia]]'' (\"civil parish\"), located in the municipality of [[Barcelos Municipality, Portugal|Barcelos]]. The population in 2011 was 680,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 6.29&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Barcelos}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panque"}
{"title_page": "Pampilhosa da Serra", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Pampilhosa da Serra\n|image_flag         = Pt-pps1.png\n|image_shield       = PPS.png\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_location     = LocalPampilhosaDaSerra.svg\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Coimbra]]\n|district           = [[Coimbra District|Coimbra]]\n|parishes           = 8\n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|03|N|7|57|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 396.46\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 4,481\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|website            = {{url|http://www.cm-pampilhosadaserra.pt}}\n}}\n\n'''Pampilhosa da Serra''' ({{IPA-pt|p\u0250\u0303pi\u02c8\u028e\u0254z\u0250 \u00f0\u0250 \u02c8s\u025b\u0281\u0250|-|Pt-pt Pampilhosa da Serra FF.ogg}}) is a town and a municipality in the [[Coimbra District]], in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 4,481,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 396.46&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==Parishes==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 8 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 88|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=29 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Cabril\n* Dornelas do Z\u00eazere\n* Faj\u00e3o - Vidual\n* Janeiro de Baixo\n* Pampilhosa da Serra\n* Pessegueiro\n* Portela do Fojo - Machio\n* Unhais-o-Velho\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Coimbra}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Coimbra District]]\n\n\n{{Coimbra-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Pampilhosa da Serra\n|image_flag         = Pt-pps1.png\n|image_shield       = PPS.png\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_location     = LocalPampilhosaDaSerra.svg\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Coimbra]]\n|district           = [[Coimbra District|Coimbra]]\n|parishes           = 8\n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|03|N|7|57|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 396.46\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 4,481\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|website            = {{url|http://www.cm-pampilhosadaserra.pt}}\n}}\n\n'''Pampilhosa da Serra''' ({{IPA-pt|p\u0250\u0303pi\u02c8\u028e\u0254z\u0250 \u00f0\u0250 \u02c8s\u025b\u0281\u0250|-|Pt-pt Pampilhosa da Serra FF.ogg}}) is a town and a municipality in the [[Coimbra District]], in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 4,481,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 396.46&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\n==Parishes==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 8 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 88|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=29 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Cabril\n* Dornelas do Z\u00eazere\n* Faj\u00e3o - Vidual\n* Janeiro de Baixo\n* Pampilhosa da Serra\n* Pessegueiro\n* Portela do Fojo - Machio\n* Unhais-o-Velho\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Coimbra}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Coimbra District]]\n\n\n{{Coimbra-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pampilhosa_da_Serra"}
{"title_page": "Jacques Pellen", "text_new": "{{short description|French composer, musician and guitarist}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n[[Image: Celtic Procession.jpg |thumb|right|220px|Jacques Pellen]]\n\n'''Jacques Pellen''', (1957 in Brest - 21 April 2020) was a French jazz guitarist. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/amp/infos/culture-loisirs/coronavirus-le-guitariste-breton-jacques-pellen-est-decede-1587469449|title=Coronavirus : le guitariste breton Jacques Pellen est d\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9|date=21 April 2020|website=France Bleu|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He died of [[COVID-19]] in April 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://world-today-news.com/guitarist-jacques-pellen-dies-brittany/|title=Guitarist Jacques Pellen dies \u2013 Brittany|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>  Pellen worked with many musicians over the years such as Peter Gritz, Kenny Wheeler, Bruno Nevez, Henri Texier, Riccardo Del Fra, and violinist Didier Lockwood.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pellen, Jacques}}\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century French musicians]]\n[[Category:French jazz guitarists]]\n\n\n{{France-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French composer, musician and guitarist}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n[[Image: Celtic Procession.jpg |thumb|right|220px|Jacques Pellen]]\n\n'''Jacques Pellen''', (1957 in Brest - 21 April 2020) was a French jazz guitarist. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/amp/infos/culture-loisirs/coronavirus-le-guitariste-breton-jacques-pellen-est-decede-1587469449|title=Coronavirus : le guitariste breton Jacques Pellen est d\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9|date=21 April 2020|website=France Bleu|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He died of [[COVID-19]] in April 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://world-today-news.com/guitarist-jacques-pellen-dies-brittany/|title=Guitarist Jacques Pellen dies \u2013 Brittany|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>  Pellen worked with many musicians over the years; such as, Peter Gritz, Kenny Wheeler, Bruno Nevez, Henri Texier, Riccardo Del Fra and violinist Didier Lockwood.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pellen, Jacques }}\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century French musicians]]\n[[Category:French jazz guitarists]]\n\n\n{{France-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Poydoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Pellen"}
{"title_page": "Frank J. Williams", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{About|the jurist and Lincoln scholar from Rhode Island (USA)|other people named \"Frank Williams\"|Frank Williams (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox judge\n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = Frank J. Williams\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = \n | alt         = \n | caption     = \n | office      =  Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Rhode Island]]\n | term_start  =  2001\n | term_end    =  2008\n | nominator   =  \n | appointer   =  [[Lincoln Almond]]\n | predecessor =  [[Joseph R. Weisberger]]\n | successor   =  [[Paul Suttell]]\n| pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1940|08|24}}\n | birth_place     = [[Richmond, Rhode Island]]\n | death_date      =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place     = \n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = [[Americans|American]]\n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = [[Boston University]]<br/>[[Boston University School of Law]]<br/>[[Bryant University]]\n | alma_mater      = \n | occupation      = \n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | salary          = \n | net_worth       =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | awards          =  Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]]<br/>The Order of Lincoln\n | blank1          = \n | data1           = \n | blank2          = \n | data2           = \n | blank3          = \n | data3           = \n | blank4          = \n | data4           = \n | blank5          = \n | data5           = \n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n | website         = \n<!--Military service-->\n | nickname        = \n | allegiance      = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]]\n | branch          = {{flagicon|USA|army}} [[United States Army]]\n | serviceyears    = \n | rank            = [[File:Army-USA-OF-02.svg|30px]] [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n | unit            = \n | commands        = \n | battles         = \n | mawards         =  [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]]<br/>Three [[Air Medal|Air Medals]]<br/>[[Army Commendation Medal]]<br/>[[National Defense Service Medal]]<br/>[[Vietnam Service Medal]]<br/>[[Republic of Vietnam Cross of Gallantry]]<br/>[[Republic of Vietnam Campaign Medal]]\n | military_blank1 = \n | military_data1  = \n | military_blank2 = \n | military_data2  = \n | military_blank3 = \n | military_data3  = \n | military_blank4 = \n | military_data4  = \n | military_blank5 = \n | military_data5  = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n | module          = \n | module2         = \n | module3         = \n | module4         = \n | module5         = \n | footnotes       = \n}}\n[[Image:Some judges on the Court of Military Commission Review.jpg|thumb|Frank Williams is in the center on right side]]\n'''Frank J. Williams''' (born August 24, 1940) is a former Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Rhode Island]], a notable [[Abraham Lincoln]] scholar and author, and a Justice of the Military Commission Review Panel.<ref name=DoD2004-09-22>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25238 \n |title=Military Commission Review Panel Takes Oath of Office \n |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] \n |date=2004-09-22 \n |accessdate=2008-11-02 \n |quote=Chief Justice Frank Williams, chief justice of the Rhode Island Supreme Court. Williams was as an associate justice of the Superior Court of Rhode Island from 1995 to 2001. He served as an Army captain in Vietnam, earning the Bronze Star, the Combat Infantry Badge, and the Republic of Vietnam Gallantry Cross with Silver Star for Valor. He earned his law degree from Boston University in 1970 and a master's degree in taxation from Bryant College in 1986. \n |url-status=bot: unknown \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023120601/http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25238 \n |archivedate=2008-10-23 \n}} \n</ref><ref name=JagMagJudgeExpertise>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/JAGMAG/Winter_Navy%20Judges%20Lend%20Expertise%20to%20the%20Court%20of%20Military%20Commission%20Review.pdf \n |title=Navy Judges Lend Expertise to the Court of Military Commission Review \n |author=[[Jason Jones (Judge Advocate General)|Jason Jones]] \n |accessdate=2008-09-11 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5c27uHqhK?url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/JAGMAG/Winter_Navy%20Judges%20Lend%20Expertise%20to%20the%20Court%20of%20Military%20Commission%20Review.pdf \n |archivedate=November 2, 2008 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nFrank Williams was born in [[Richmond, Rhode Island]] in 1940 to Italian immigrants.<ref>Lincoln Lessons: Reflections on America's Greatest Leader, edited by Frank J. Williams and William D. Pederson, Mario M Cuomo, pg. 17 [https://books.google.com/books?id=yDXZc5gV4-sC&pg=PA160&lpg=PA160&dq=frank+j.+williams+italian&source=bl&ots=W7vmRfxGjo&sig=LKOEoCnSZHBaAoe_mcsK0CWToGs&hl=en&ei=mVfPSrmzG8HhlAe9ls2oCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6#v=onepage&q=frank j. williams italian&f=false]</ref>  He graduated from [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]] East High School, [[Boston University]] and [[Boston University School of Law]], and he received masters in taxation from [[Bryant University]].\n\nFrom 1962 to 1967, he served as a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] in the [[U.S. Army]] and was stationed in Germany and [[Vietnam war|Vietnam]].\n\nHis military awards include the [[Combat Infantryman Badge]] and [[Bronze Star Medal]], three [[Air Medal]]s and the [[Army Commendation Medal]], the [[National Defense Service Medal]], [[Vietnam Service Medal]] with two campaign stars the [[Republic of Vietnam Cross of Gallantry]] with silver citation star and [[Republic of Vietnam Campaign Medal]] for his military service.<ref name=DoD2004-09-22/><ref>http://www.stjohns.edu/academics/graduate/law/alumni/calendar/ev_law_080204.event@digest.stjohns.edu%2facademics%2fgraduate%2flaw%2fev_law_080204.xml</ref>\n\nHe served as town moderator of [[Richmond, Rhode Island]], and town solicitor.  Governor [[Lincoln Almond]] appointed Williams to the Supreme Court in 1995.  He was elevated to Chief Justice of the Supreme Court in 2001.\n\nIn 2003, President Bush appointed Williams through the Secretary of Defense to be a member of the [[United States Court of Military Commission Review]].<ref name=DoD2004-09-22/>  As of July 2007, he replaced [[Griffin Bell]] as the Chief Judge.<ref name=JagMagJudgeExpertise/> He served as Chief Judge of the [[United States Court of Military Commission Review|US Court of Military Commissions]] until December 2009.\n\nHe was a member of the U.S. [[Abraham Lincoln Bicentennial Commission]] and co-founded and for 16 years has chaired The Lincoln Forum. Williams was president of the [[Abraham Lincoln Association]], the Lincoln Group of Boston, and currently serves as president of The Ulysses S. Grant Association. In 2010, Williams was elected to the board of the [[Abraham Lincoln Bicentennial Foundation]]. Justice Williams is an Associate Companion of the [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]], an organization founded by Union officers who served during the American Civil War, and is also a Veteran Companion of the [[Military Order of Foreign Wars]]. Williams was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State\u2019s highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 2009 as a Bicentennial Laureate.\n\nFrank J. Williams stepped down from the Rhode Island Supreme Court at the end of December 2009 and has lectured at several universities and institutes, most notably at the New Hampshire Institute of Politics at [[Saint Anselm College]]. Williams is also an accomplished amateur chef, having appeared as a guest on the cooking show, ''[[Ciao Italia]]'', with [[Mary Ann Esposito]].<ref>[http://www.ricentral.com/content/view/142783/239/ Chief Justice Frank Williams steps down], \"The Chariho Times\" (December 23, 2008).</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nFrank J. Williams  was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State\u2019s highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 2009 as a Bicentennial Laureate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-7|title=Laureates by Year - The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|website=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.state.ri.us/govtracker/index.php?page=DetailJudge&rid=2262 Official Secretary of State site]\n*[http://www.ExactingEditor.com/FrankWilliams.html Interview with Justice Williams about his life and literary work] (the Exacting Editor)\n*{{C-SPAN|Frank Williams}}\n**[http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/172900-1/Frank+Williams.aspx ''Booknotes'' interview with Williams on ''Judging Lincoln'', November 10, 2002.]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Frank J.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island Republicans]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Rhode Island Supreme Court]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Historians of Abraham Lincoln]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{About|the jurist and Lincoln scholar from Rhode Island (USA)|other people named \"Frank Williams\"|Frank Williams (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox judge\n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = Frank J. Williams\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = \n | alt         = \n | caption     = \n | office      =  Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Rhode Island]]\n | term_start  =  2001\n | term_end    =  2008\n | nominator   =  \n | appointer   =  [[Lincoln Almond]]\n | predecessor =  [[Joseph R. Weisberger]]\n | successor   =  [[Paul Suttell]]\n| pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1940|08|24}}\n | birth_place     = [[Richmond, Rhode Island]]\n | death_date      =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place     = \n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = [[Americans|American]]\n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optiona