en/theme_conferences_1864.html?p=1 ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography,'' \"The Charlottetown and Quebec Conferences of 1864\"]\n\n{{Constitution of Canada|Confederation}}\n{{History of Canada navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|History|Canada|Politics}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian Confederation| ]]\n[[Category:1840s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1850s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1860s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1867 in Canada]]\n[[Category:Federalism in Canada]]\n[[Category:History of Canada]]\n[[Category:National unifications]]\n[[Category:Political history of Canada]]\n[[Category:British North America]]\n[[Category:Pre-Confederation Canada]]\n[[Category:Post-Confederation Canada (1867\u20131914)]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in Canada|*]]\n[[Category:1867 in Canadian law]]\n[[Category:1867 in politics]]\n[[Category:19th century in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "74.127.203.248", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Confederation"}
{"title_page": "Palmela", "text_new": "{{For|the Count, Marquess and Duke of Palmela, and also Duke of Faial|Pedro de Sousa Holstein}}\n\n{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n| official_name   = Palmela\n| image_flag      = Pt-plm1.png\n| image_shield    = PLM.png\n| image_skyline   = \n| image_caption   = \n|coordinates             = {{coord|38|40|N|8|58|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map       = LocalPalmela.svg\n|region             = [[Lisboa Region|Lisbon]]\n|metro              = [[Lisbon metropolitan area|Lisbon]]\n|district           = [[Set\u00fabal District|Set\u00fabal]]\n| leader_party            = [[Unitarian Democratic Coalition|CDU]]\n| leader_name             = [[Ana Teresa Vicente]]\n| area_total_km2          = 465.12\n| population_total        = 62,831\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| parishes        = [[#Parishes|4]]\n| holiday = 1 June\n| website                 = http://www.cm-palmela.pt\n}}\n'''Palmela''' ({{IPA-pt|pal\u02c8m\u025bl\u0250|-|Pt-pt Palmela FF.ogg}}) is a town and a municipality in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 62,831,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 465.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\nThe municipality is located in [[Set\u00fabal District]], about {{convert|25|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Lisbon]]. The municipal holiday is 1 June.\n\n==Parishes==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, pages 552 87-88|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=29 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Palmela\n* [[Pinhal Novo]]\n* Poceir\u00e3o e Marateca\n* Quinta do Anjo\n\n==General information==\n[[Image:Castelo Palmela e Camara.JPG|thumb|left|View of Palmela, with the Municipality building (foreground) and castle uphill.]]\n[[Image:Castelo Palmela e Vale Barris.JPG|thumb|left|Castle of Palmela and surrounding landscape.]]\nThe area has been settled since at least Neolithic times, as evidenced by excavations at places such as the [[artificial caves of Casal do Pardo]] and the [[Castro of Chibanes]]. The town's name comes from its [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] founder, [[Cornelius Palma]] (''Palmella''). Palmela, once a fortress, was conquered by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] in the 12th century. A semi-rural town, it is located up a hill in the [[Arr\u00e1bida]] area, right in the middle of Portugal's biggest urban area. Many people are moving in from big cities like [[Lisbon]]. Wild fires in the region are a threat to the environment.\n\nThe castle, [[Castelo de Palmela]], offers a unique view over the whole region of the [[Set\u00fabal Peninsula]], Lisbon, and the [[Atlantic]] Coast. It was a strategic place in past centuries, and today it is still a main juncture of Portugal's road and rail networks.\n\nPalmela is home to many multinational industrial plants like [[Volkswagen]] and [[Coca-Cola]], and a significant number of foreign families live in the area. The local radio often broadcasts in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]].\n\nPalmela's traditional products are the wine, which has achieved international awards in several festivals like [[Bordeaux Wine Festival|Bordeaux's]], and the ''[[Queijo de Azeit\u00e3o]]'' ([[Azeit\u00e3o]]'s cheese). There are several festivals dedicated to these products, the most famous being the ''Festa das Vindimas'' (Vines' Festival) and the ''Festival do Queijo, P\u00e3o e Vinho'' (Festival of Cheese, Bread and Wine).\n\nPalmela is the birthplace of the Portuguese explorer [[Hermenegildo Capelo]]. Some other famous individuals such as [[Hans Christian Andersen]] were briefly hosted there.\n\n==Economy==\nThe municipality is famous for its production of fruit and wine.\n\nIn the 1990s, the joint-venture [[Volkswagen]]-[[Ford]] [[AutoEuropa]] vehicle production plant opened, to produce the Mk1 MPV sold under three [[marque]]s: [[Volkswagen Sharan]], [[SEAT Alhambra]] and [[Ford Galaxy]]. After Ford left the joint venture, the plant has since continued to produce the Volkswagen and SEAT products, and added the [[Volkswagen Eos]], [[Volkswagen Scirocco]] and [[Volkswagen Taigun|Taigun]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Palmela IPR]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Palmela}}\n*[http://www.cm-palmela.pt/ Town Hall official website]\n*[http://sig.cm-palmela.pt/ GIS official website]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/vitor107/sets/72057594052758963/ Photos from Palmela]\n\n{{Municipalities of Set\u00fabal}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Set\u00fabal District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Set\u00fabal District]]\n[[Category:Towns in Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Count, Marquess and Duke of Palmela, and also Duke of Faial|Pedro de Sousa Holstein}}\n\n{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n| official_name   = Palmela\n| image_flag      = Pt-plm1.png\n| image_shield    = PLM.png\n| image_skyline   = \n| image_caption   = \n|coordinates             = {{coord|38|40|N|8|58|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map       = LocalPalmela.svg\n|region             = [[Lisboa Region|Lisbon]]\n|metro              = [[Lisbon metropolitan area|Lisbon]]\n|district           = [[Set\u00fabal District|Set\u00fabal]]\n| leader_party            = [[Unitarian Democratic Coalition|CDU]]\n| leader_name             = [[Ana Teresa Vicente]]\n| area_total_km2          = 465.12\n| population_total        = 62,831\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| parishes        = [[#Parishes|4]]\n| holiday = 1 June\n| website                 = http://www.cm-palmela.pt\n}}\n'''Palmela''' ({{IPA-pt|pal\u02c8m\u025bl\u0250|-|Pt-pt Palmela FF.ogg}}) is a town and a municipality in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 62,831,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 465.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>[http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ \u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds]</ref>\n\nThe municipality is located in [[Set\u00fabal District]], about {{convert|25|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Lisbon]]. The municipal holiday is 1 June.\n\n==Parishes==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, pages 552 87-88|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=29 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Palmela\n* [[Pinhal Novo]]\n* Poceir\u00e3o e Marateca\n* Quinta do Anjo\n\n==General information==\n[[Image:Castelo Palmela e Camara.JPG|thumb|left|View of Palmela, with the Municipality building (foreground) and castle uphill.]]\n[[Image:Castelo Palmela e Vale Barris.JPG|thumb|left|Castle of Palmela and surrounding landscape.]]\nThe area has been settled since at least Neolithic times, as evidenced by excavations at places such as the [[artificial caves of Casal do Pardo]] and the [[Castro of Chibanes]]. The town's name comes from its [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] founder, [[Cornelius Palma]] (''Palmella''). Palmela, once a fortress, was conquered by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] in the 12th century. A semi-rural town, it is located up a hill in the [[Arr\u00e1bida]] area, right in the middle of Portugal's biggest urban area. Many people are moving in from big cities like [[Lisbon]]. Wild fires in the region are a threat to the environment.\n\nThe castle, [[Castelo de Palmela]], offers a unique view over the whole region of the [[Set\u00fabal Peninsula]], Lisbon, and the [[Atlantic]] Coast. It was a strategic place in past centuries, and today it is still a main juncture of Portugal's road and rail networks.\n\nPalmela is home to many multinational industrial plants like [[Volkswagen]] and [[Coca-Cola]], and a significant number of foreign families live in the area. The local radio often broadcasts in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]].\n\nPalmela's traditional products are the wine, which has achieved international awards in several festivals like [[Bordeaux Wine Festival|Bordeaux's]], and the ''[[Queijo de Azeit\u00e3o]]'' ([[Azeit\u00e3o]]'s cheese). There are several festivals dedicated to these products, the most famous being the ''Festa das Vindimas'' (Vines' Festival) and the ''Festival do Queijo, P\u00e3o e Vinho'' (Festival of Cheese, Bread and Wine).\n\nPalmela is the birthplace of the Portuguese explorer [[Hermenegildo Capelo]]. Some other famous individuals such as [[Hans Christian Andersen]] were briefly hosted there.\n\n==Economy==\nThe municipality is famous for its production of fruit and wine.\n\nIn the 1990s, the joint-venture [[Volkswagen]]-[[Ford]] [[AutoEuropa]] vehicle production plant opened, to produce the Mk1 MPV sold under three [[marque]]s: [[Volkswagen Sharan]], [[SEAT Alhambra]] and [[Ford Galaxy]]. After Ford left the joint venture, the plant has since continued to produce the Volkswagen and SEAT products, and added the [[Volkswagen Eos]], [[Volkswagen Scirocco]] and [[Volkswagen Taigun|Taigun]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Palmela IPR]]\n\n==References==\n{{